      <h1>401k Explained: How Much Should You Contribute in 2025?</h1>
      <div class="article-meta"><span>Jun 12, 2025</span><span>·</span><span>6 min read</span></div>
      <p class="article-intro">A 401k is the most powerful tax-saving tool available to US employees. Here is everything you need to know — contribution limits, employer match, and how much to save at your income level.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container" style="max-width:740px;">
    <div class="prose">
      <div class="callout"><strong>See your 401k tax savings →</strong> Enter your salary and 401k % in our <a href="/salary-calculator">take-home pay calculator</a> to see how much tax you save.</div>

      <h2>What is a 401k?</h2>
      <p>A 401k is an employer-sponsored retirement savings plan. You contribute a portion of your paycheck — pre-tax — and the money grows tax-deferred until retirement. Many employers match a portion of your contributions, which is essentially free money.</p>

      <h2>2025 401k contribution limits</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Employee limit:</strong> $23,500/year</li>
        <li><strong>Catch-up (age 50+):</strong> Additional $7,500 = $31,000 total</li>
        <li><strong>Super catch-up (age 60-63):</strong> Additional $11,250 = $34,750 total (new in 2025)</li>
        <li><strong>Total limit (employee + employer):</strong> $70,000</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Traditional 401k vs Roth 401k</h2>
      <table>
        <tr><th>Feature</th><th>Traditional 401k</th><th>Roth 401k</th></tr>
        <tr><td>Contributions</td><td>Pre-tax (reduces income now)</td><td>After-tax (no immediate benefit)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Withdrawals</td><td>Taxed as income</td><td>Tax-free (if qualified)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Best for</td><td>High earners now, lower income in retirement</td><td>Lower earners now, higher income expected</td></tr>
        <tr><td>RMDs</td><td>Required at 73</td><td>No RMDs</td></tr>
      </table>

      <h2>How much should you contribute?</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Minimum:</strong> Always contribute at least enough to get the full employer match. If your employer matches 50% up to 6%, contribute 6% — otherwise you're leaving free money behind.</li>
        <li><strong>Standard:</strong> 10-15% of salary is the commonly recommended target for retirement security.</li>
        <li><strong>Aggressive:</strong> Max out the $23,500 limit if you can afford it — especially valuable in your 30s and 40s due to compound growth.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>How 401k reduces your taxes (real example)</h2>
      <p>On a $65,000 salary contributing 6% ($3,900):</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Taxable income drops from $65,000 to $61,100</li>
        <li>Federal tax savings: ~$858/year (in 22% bracket)</li>
        <li>Your paycheck decreases by only ~$54/month — but you're saving $325/month</li>
        <li>Plus employer match: if 50% match on 6%, that's $1,950 free per year</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>When can you withdraw 401k money?</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Age 59½:</strong> Penalty-free withdrawals begin</li>
        <li><strong>Age 73:</strong> Required Minimum Distributions (RMDs) begin for traditional 401k</li>
        <li><strong>Early withdrawal:</strong> 10% penalty + income tax (with some exceptions)</li>
        <li><strong>Loans:</strong> Many plans allow borrowing up to 50% of balance or $50,000</li>
      </ul>

